Drone racing trajectory planner — current benchmark: 0.809 (20 rollouts, 4 levels × 5 seeds).

Architecture: cubic spline through start → liftoff → (approach, center, exit)×gates,
constant arc-speed timing at 1.5 m/s. Position-only Mellinger commands (vel/acc=0).

HIGHEST-IMPACT IMPROVEMENTS TO TRY (in priority order):

1. SPEED: Raise CRUISE_SPEED to 2.0–2.2 m/s, MAX_SPEED to 3.0 m/s.
   The 1.5 m/s cruise is leaving ~30% lap-time on the table. Mellinger tracks
   reliably up to ~3 m/s. More speed = lower lap_time = higher score, especially
   for L0/L1 where the track is fixed and predictable.

2. APPROACH ALIGNMENT: Compute flow_dir as the vector from the PREVIOUS gate center
   (not the previous waypoint cluster) through the current gate center. This gives
   a cleaner, more consistent approach angle (<20°) and avoids the spline curling
   back when approach/exit waypoints are placed relative to an already-offset prev.

3. DROP THE CENTER WAYPOINT: Spline through approach and exit only — omit the
   explicit gate-center waypoint. Fewer knots → smoother curvature → less
   overshoot and oscillation mid-gate. Keep APPROACH_DIST=0.6m, EXIT_DIST=0.6m
   so the drone crosses cleanly through the 0.36m gate frame.

4. LIFTOFF TUNING: Current liftoff_frac=0.5 often undershoots gate 0 altitude.
   Set liftoff z = gate0_z + 0.1 m directly (not a fraction of delta), and move
   the liftoff xy 30% of the way to gate 0 (not 20%) to flatten the initial arc.

5. OBSTACLE AVOIDANCE COMPLETENESS: Check every waypoint in the list against
   all obstacle bubbles, not just approach/exit. Use 0.25m safety radius.
   After nudging, re-check the nudged point (obstacles can be clustered).

6. SPLINE ENDPOINT BCS: Switch from "not-a-knot" to clamped BCs at the start
   (`bc_type=((1, [0,0,0]), "not-a-knot")`) so the drone launches forward
   rather than curling backward from the start waypoint.

Level weights: L0=1.0, L1=1.5, L2=2.0, L3=3.0. L3 uses random track layouts
per seed — every improvement must generalize. Never hardcode gate positions.
